<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 1) Do you try to build assymetry into your models (deliberately or by not mirroring one side and welding the two),  or do you leave it to the skeleton and animation to deform the (symmetrical) model assymetrically? Do you have a say in how the skeletons are built/ how the design looks?<P>
 
 2) Do you think moving to patch-based modelling for games will be easy for you? i.e do you think you get too used to certain conventions when working low-poly? Do you think in general that low polygon models look 'stylised and cool' and high res versions tend to lose something? (maybe its just me)<P>
 
 Thanks!<P>
 
 CJH

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   (1) I don't bother with asymmetry unless the model requires it (for
example, the disembodied hand).  Generally, I build half a model,
then mirror it and weld the two halves together, as you've guessed.
This is naturally much more efficient than building the entire model,
especially with regard to texture mapping.<P>

   (2) Patch-based modeling will be a breeze for me, especially since
I do it fairly regularly, anyway (I sometimes convert NURBS
geometry to polygonal geometry) -- and I'll take a high-resolution
polygonal model over a blocky one pretty much any day of the
week.<P>

